fun_facts.about_msg_list:
Try to fold a piece paper 6 times, remember to fold it completely over itself at each repetition. Can you fold it a seventh time? An eighth? How far can you go? Maybe we need a larger piece of paper to begin with! It was thought for years that 7 was the maximum number of times a piece of paper could be folded, but in 2002 American teenager Britney Gallivan demonstrated that a sheet of paper can be folded 12 times, provided that it is long enough and thin enough.  Britney Gallivan demonstrated this by using a 1200m length of toilet paper, which provided her with both the length and thinness which she required.  Britney even came up with a formula that showed how long the piece of paper would have to be able to fold it n times:
;
L = π×t×(2ⁿ + 4)(2ⁿ - 1) ∕ 6
;
L is the length of paper required, t is the thickness of the paper and n is how many folds you can make.
;
Ten years later in 2012 a group of students beat Britney's record by taking 16km of toilet roll and folding it in one direction 13 times.

